   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "23cb151a-e541-477d-9c40-5a7231966ab8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# kmerExtractor user manual"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3104a0cc-27b1-4507-9b28-5b8208f34685",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A genome sequence is composed of four basic types of nucleotides: adenine (A), cytosine (C), guanine (G), and thymine (T). \n",
    "All possible nucleotide substrings of length $k$ are called **k-mers**. For example, for $k=2$ there are $4^k=4^2=16$ different 2-mers corresponding to: AA, AC, AG, AT, CA, CC, CG, CT, GA, GC, GG, GT, TA, TC, TG, TT.\n",
    "\n",
    "The kmerExtractor software calculates the k-mer frequencies for windows within the chromosomes of an organism's sequence. \n",
    "It takes as input a FASTA file with the nucleotide sequence of an organism separated by chromosomes. The software splits the chromosomes into windows of the size specified by the user. For a given $k$, the kmerExtractor computes the frequency of the k-mers in the different windows within the chromosomes. It returns a csv file indicating the chromosome, the window index, the start and end position of the window, and the frequencies of the corresponding k-mers. \n",
    "\n",
    "Below we present examples of how to use the different functions of the software. See section X for more technical details on each function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "77671313-293d-4507-9a5d-c26efd8705ec",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Import libraries"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "2f801588-edda-4599-b960-da4f311863d5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "# software to extract the k-mers\n",
    "import kmerExtractor as kex"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b3fbcd84-ec6b-4dcc-b530-c3b2743285ca",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Compute k-mers\n",
    "\n",
    "Specify the corresponding directory of the FASTA files from which you want to extract the k-mers, and the directory where you want to save the output files. Also define the window size (in base pairs) for which you want the frequency of k-mers to be counted. \n",
    "\n",
    "In this case we will use the genome of arabidospsis, tomato and maize, with a window size of $100000$ bp for all genomes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "86c0e3ec-244e-4e5c-b016-c8b23c276e64",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "filepath_ara = '../input_data/arabidopsis_genome.fasta'\n",
    "filepath_tom = '../input_data/tomato_genome.fasta'\n",
    "filepath_mz = '../input_data/maize_genome.fasta'\n",
    "output_path = '../output_data'\n",
    "window_size = 100_000"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d33cc6b1-5861-4c4c-90c6-4d5e1f38751a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now use the kmers_by_window function to calculate the k-mers of each genome for the $k$ of your choice.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the output file, the first column indicates the chromosome, the second column the window index, the third and fourth columns indicate the start and end position of the window respectively, and the rest of the $4^k$ columns correspond to the k-mer frequencies. This data is saved in a csv file and stored in a dataframe for downstream analysis within the notebook.\n",
    "\n",
    " \n",
    "The resulting dataframe for arabidopsis looks like below."
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6a1fbcfa-38c6-4979-9ef1-fc870abe0dab",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Read k-mer files if already computed"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e6e5d4e6-37c0-49c6-b15b-a967bcd10c34",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As seen in the cells above, calculating k-mers can take longer for larger genomes, e.g., almost 12 minutes for the maiz genome with ~152 Mb. That's why you also have the option to load previously saved files, so you don't have to recalculate the k-mers every time you want to plot some figures or do further analysis.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "15c7371b-8bff-4ec0-b7e5-907172373ba6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "df_2mers_ara = pd.read_csv(output_path +'/CGRW_k2_arabidopsis_genome.csv')\n",
    "df_2mers_tom = pd.read_csv(output_path +'/CGRW_k2_tomato_genome.csv')\n",
    "df_2mers_mz = pd.read_csv(output_path +'/CGRW_k2_maize_genome.csv')\n",
    "\n",
    "df_3mers_ara = pd.read_csv(output_path +'/CGRW_k3_arabidopsis_genome.csv')\n",
    "df_3mers_tom = pd.read_csv(output_path +'/CGRW_k3_tomato_genome.csv')\n",
    "df_3mers_mz = pd.read_csv(output_path +'/CGRW_k3_maize_genome.csv')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a06f41cc-f405-41c0-8ba8-1f761763dc0b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Group all windows within each chromosome"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "538eb323-3fd8-4786-8729-52d97f620963",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

  },

   "source": [
    "## k-mer figures"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7da09ea0-12da-4e83-993a-8b884bd2b376",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Plot k-mers across windows"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "dd5c9c4c-2116-444b-8b5f-180d3e2b3cd2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "With the plot_kmers_across_windows function you can plot the frequencies of the k-mers of your choice across the windows of a specified chromosome."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "f7b92e64-322f-4496-8bb5-216d267f8555",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

      ]
     },

      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "a = kex.plot_kmers_across_windows(df_2mers_ara,['TT','CC'],'chr1')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ab335f87-54a6-4ac1-84ac-c27b6a53968a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You can also use this function to compare, placing the plot of different chromosomes on different axes within the same figure."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "641a0a71-7f16-43af-8e12-30949152599f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",

       "<Figure size 864x720 with 2 Axes>"
      ]

     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig,ax = plt.subplots(2,1,figsize=(12,10),gridspec_kw={'hspace': 0.3})\n",
    "\n",
    "kex.plot_kmers_across_windows(df_3mers_ara,['TTT','CCC'],'chr1',ax=ax[0])\n",
    "kex.plot_kmers_across_windows(df_3mers_ara,['TTT','CCC'],'chr4',ax=ax[1])\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "81ff6f15-63fe-4833-9c48-cbfc5e18df78",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

   "id": "09abfb3a-f76e-49c1-aaaf-3f00efc68f83",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The X function makes a stacked bar graph of the frequency of different k-mers per chromosome. For the same k-mer, each stacked bar represents a different chromosome of the corresponding color."
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0b672037-b4d2-4136-9112-0875657f7555",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Plot FCGR structure"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "72e7128b-0e4a-44fb-9cf0-0d2de1667673",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The way of depict the frequency of k-mers is known as Frequency Chaos Game Representation (FCGR). It corresponds to a matrix of dimensions $N \\times N$, where $N = 4^{k/2}$; with the upper left corner equal to the k-mer of C, the upper right corner the k-mer of G, the lower left corner the k-mer of A, and the lower right corner the k-mer of T.\n",
    "The plot_FCGR function plots the FCGR of a sequence as a heatmap that allows to appreciate the relative frequencies of each k-mer. You can plot the FCGR for a specific chromosome and window, the cumulative frequency for an entire chromosome (if no window is specified), or the cumulative frequency for the entire sequence (if neither chromosome nor window is specified)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "39508ad4-e701-46e5-ad80-51b3860ede38",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 504x432 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "d = kex.plot_FCGR(df_3mers_ara,'chr1',window=145)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "47f67915-3c85-4f61-89d3-0cefcedfca89",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You can also adjust the size of the figure and the colormap to your preference as shown below"
   ]
  },

   "id": "f9645a5a-3cb6-4615-a3de-8300d90f6440",
   "metadata": {},

     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "e = kex.plot_FCGR(df_2mers_tom,'chr6',figsize=(4,3),colormap='Greys')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

   "source": [

    "ax[2].set_title('Maize')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
